  "prompt": "What is 6/6 myopia vision?",
  "response": "\"6/6 myopia vision\" refers to a standard measurement of visual acuity, often used in eye examinations. The term \"6/6\" (or \"20/20\" in some countries) indicates that a person can see at 6 meters (or 20 feet) what a person with normal vision should be able to see at that distance. \n\nHowever, \"6/6\" does not specifically indicate myopia (nearsightedness). Myopia is a condition where distant objects appear blurry, and it is typically measured with a negative value in diopters (e.g., -1.00 D, -2.00 D). \n\nSo, if someone has \"6/6 myopia vision,\" it means they have normal visual acuity at 6 meters when corrected with lenses for their myopia. In other words, with their glasses or contact lenses, they can see 6/6, but without correction, they would have difficulty seeing distant objects clearly.\n\nTo summarize:\n- \"6/6\" indicates normal visual acuity at 6 meters.\n- \"Myopia\" indicates nearsightedness, which requires corrective lenses.\n- \"6/6 myopia vision\" means that with correction, the person's vision is normal at 6 meters.",
